05147nam a22007095i 9781442678590DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181997onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426785907 a10.3138/97814426785902doi  a(DE-B1597)497070  a(OCoLC)1078918167  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a363.21 aEricson, Richard V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolicing the Risk Society /cRichard V. Ericson, Kevin D. Haggerty. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (448 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Policing -- t1. Policing as Risk Communications -- t2. Policing, Risk, and Law -- t3. Community Policing and Risk Communications -- tPART II. The Risk Society -- t4. Risk Discourse -- t5. Risk Institutions -- t6. Risk and Social Change -- tPART III. Risks to Territories -- t7. Tracing Territories -- t8. Mobilizing Territories -- t9. Territorial Communities -- tPART IV. Risks to Securities, Careers, and Identities -- t10. Securities -- t11. Careers -- t12. Identities -- tPART V. Risks to Police Organization -- t13. Knowledge Risk Management -- t14. Communication Rules -- t15. Communication Formats -- t16. Communication Technologies -- tSummary and Conclusions -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe information age has left few of us untouched; individuals and institutions alike have undergone radical transformations in the race to get the most out of new technologies. The police are no exception. Policing the Risk Society introduces us to a shocking new vision of police work in which information gathered by the police with surveillance and data collection technologies is brokered to other institutions.Richard Ericson and Kevin Haggerty contend that the police have become information brokers to institutions, such as insurance companies and health and welfare organizations whose operations are based on a knowledge of risk. These institutions influence the ways in which police officers think and act. A critical review of existing research reveals the need to study police interaction with institutions as well as with individuals. These institutions are part of an emerging 'risk society' where knowledge of risk is used to control danger. The authors examine different aspects of police involvement: the use of surveillance technologies and the collection of data on securities, careers, and different social, ethnic, age, and gender groups. They conclude by looking at how police organizations have been forced to bureaucratize and to continually adapt rules, formats, and technologies of communication to meet external demands for knowledge of risk.With this book, Ericson and Haggerty revolutionize the study of policing and, for the first time, provide concrete evidence of the central tenets of risk society theory. Their work will have a major impact not only on scholars in criminology, social theory, and communications, but on policing as well.Awarded the 1998 Herbert Jacob Book Prize by its Committee of the Law and Society Association, University of Massachusetts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolice. 0aRisk communication. 0aRisk management. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aHaggerty, Kevin D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHood, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442678590